          "user_thumbnail": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/ACg8ocKFCwxCyeBYjH5XtdQ1l6NBa5hsSw4vjGZ6xrUU-9kLP1lI8g=s120-c-rp-mo-br100",
          "description": "I had surgery for a trigger finger that took 3 minutes. Local anesthesia, no need for time-consuming prep. My guess is that if I arrived a half hour before the scheduled time, that would have been long enough to sign consent forms, be weight, get blood pressure taken, change into hospital gown, etc. Yet I was told to arrive 1 1/2 hours before the scheduled time. Whenever/whomever I asked about it told me that was the standard procedure for all procedures. Nobody could give me a reasonable explanation about why that was so.\n\nMy procedure began around 45 minutes late, which meant I spent 4 hours for a 3 minute procedure. During the time when I was finally taken into the room for actual prep, each person who came in to do one thing or another told me that doctor would be in to talk to me \"soon,\" but nobody ever told me that there would be a delay or why that was so. If someone had said something like \"the procedures before yours took longer than expected.\n\nI need to ask that everybody I interacted with was pleasant and professional. It was the system that was at fault, none of the fine people who work within it.",
          "link": "https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURUOFo2WEZ3EAE!2m1!1s0x0:0xfbee1c1f4e712354!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgIDT8Z6XFw%7C%7C?hl=en",
          "date": "2 years ago",
